    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv into memory (do not convert timestamps). For each of metric.csv, trace.csv, and log.csv compute aggregated statistics grouped by component (cmdb_id) and KPI name (use kpi_name for metrics, trace_name for traces, log_name for logs). For each group produce: count, min(value), max(value), mean(value), P50 (median) of value, and P95 of value. Return up to the top 50 groups for each file sorted by count descending. Also, for error_logs.csv, compute count of messages per cmdb_id and return up to 20 components with their counts plus up to 5 example messages per component. Store the full aggregated tables in kernel variables for later steps but only display the requested compact aggregates." }

{
    "analysis": "From the previous Executor results: metric analysis produced many groups that 'exceed' their global P95 inside the incident window but with max_exceed_ratio == 0.0 (i.e., max == P95), which makes them unlikely to be significant faults. Log and error_logs produced no entries in the window. Trace analysis showed multiple groups with non-zero exceedances; importantly a few trace groups exhibit very large max_exceed_ratio (e.g., MG01 trace.from_dockerA1.duration_p95 and dockerA1.trace.to_MG01.duration_p95 with max_exceed_ratio ≈ 15.26 and earliest_exceed_timestamp 1614858000). Other trace groups (dockerA1/dockerA2 duration_p95, and various row_count groups) have smaller but measurable exceedances (ratios from ~0.05 up to ~0.5). These trace spikes are the strongest signals so far and likely point to service-level latency/failure rather than obvious resource (CPU/memory/disk) problems, because metrics did not show large resource deviations. Given there are two recorded failures in the 19:30–20:00 window, the next concrete step is to focus on the trace groups with the largest severity (max_exceed_ratio >= 1) to identify exact occurrence timestamps and candidate faulty components. This will let us narrow candidates for subsequent metric and log inspection around those timestamps.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the trace exceedance results saved in the kernel (trace_exceed_top / trace_window / trace_thresholds), return a compact list of trace groups where max_exceed_ratio >= 1.0. For each group return: cmdb_id, trace_name, global_p95, count_in_window, count_exceed, earliest_exceed_timestamp, max_value_in_window, max_exceed_ratio. Sort by max_exceed_ratio descending and limit to top 20 rows. (Do not print full raw time series; just this compact aggregate table.)"
}

{
    "analysis": "From prior results we identified two distinct severe trace spikes inside the incident window: one at timestamp 1614857820 (affecting MG02/dockerA2 traces) and one at 1614858000 (affecting MG01/dockerA1 traces). Metrics aggregates did not show large resource deviations (many metric groups 'met' P95 but with max_exceed_ratio == 0.0), and logs/error_logs had no entries in the broader window; therefore traces are the strongest signals. According to the diagnosis rules, the root cause component should be chosen from the provided possible root cause components (MG01, MG02, IG01, Tomcat*, Mysql*, Redis*, apache* etc.). The severe trace groups pair a MGxx service with a dockerA container for each event; since dockerA* are not in the provided allowable root-cause component list, MG01 and MG02 are prime root-cause candidates for the two failures. However, we must confirm by inspecting: (1) full trace context at the exact spike timestamps to verify downstream faulty services in the call chain, (2) metrics for allowed components at those timestamps to see any substantive resource anomalies (exceedance magnitude >50%), and (3) any logs / error_logs around those timestamps to identify reasons (e.g., network latency, high CPU, OOM, disk, etc.). The next step is to extract compact, focused telemetry at the two spike timestamps to support conclusive localization and reason inference.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For the two severe spike timestamps 1614857820 and 1614858000 perform the following (use kernel tables already stored: trace_window, trace_thresholds, metric_window, metric_thresholds, log_window, error_logs_window):\n1) Trace context: Return all trace_window rows whose timestamp is exactly 1614857820 or 1614858000. For each row include: timestamp, converted UTC+8 datetime (single string column named datetime_utc8), cmdb_id, trace_name, value. Sort by timestamp asc then value desc. Limit output to top 50 rows.\n2) Metric snapshot (allowed root-cause components only): For each of the two timestamps, retrieve metric_window rows at that timestamp where cmdb_id is in [\"apache01\",\"apache02\",\"Tomcat01\",\"Tomcat02\",\"Tomcat03\",\"Tomcat04\",\"MG01\",\"MG02\",\"IG01\",\"IG02\",\"Mysql01\",\"Mysql02\",\"Redis01\",\"Redis02\"]. Join each metric row with metric_thresholds to get global_p95 and compute exceed = (value >= global_p95) and exceed_ratio = (value - global_p95)/max(global_p95,1e-9). Return rows where exceed is True, with columns: timestamp, datetime_utc8, cmdb_id, kpi_name, value, global_p95, exceed_ratio. Sort by timestamp then exceed_ratio desc. Limit to top 50 rows.\n3) Logs and error logs around spikes: For each timestamp, return log_window and error_logs_window rows with timestamps within +/- 60 seconds of the spike (inclusive) for the same allowed components list. For each returned row include: timestamp, datetime_utc8, cmdb_id, (log_name and value) for logs, and (message) for error_logs. Limit each of the four outputs (logs per-timestamp and error_logs per-timestamp) to top 20 rows.\nKeep all full intermediate tables in kernel variables but only print the compact result tables described above. If any of the requested tables is empty, return an explicit empty-table indicator for that request."
}

{
    "analysis": "Trace analysis identified two strong, separate spikes inside the incident window: one at 1614857820 (MG02 / dockerA2-related traces) and one at 1614858000 (MG01 / dockerA1-related traces). Metrics overall did not show broad resource saturation (many metric groups only reached their global P95 but with max_exceed_ratio == 0.0). However, a few metric rows at the 1614857820 snapshot showed moderate exceed ratios (disk/network writes) and one IG02 CPU idle signal (high idle, not high load). The strongest signal for root-cause candidates comes from traces: MG02-related traces at 1614857820 (max_exceed_ratio up to ~8.9) and MG01-related traces at 1614858000 (max_exceed_ratio ~15.26). According to the diagnosis rules, MG01 and MG02 are valid root-cause candidates (they are in the allowed component list), and are likely the service-level faulty components. To confirm and determine the underlying reasons (e.g., network latency, CPU, memory, disk, JVM OOM), we must inspect the metrics for MG01 at 1614858000 and for MG02 at 1614857820 (checking whether any resource KPI shows a substantial deviation, e.g., exceed_ratio >> 0.5) and also collect trace duration KPIs for those components at the spike times. Logs and error_logs were empty in prior broader queries, but we should re-check ±60s around each spike for MG01 and MG02 to confirm absence of log clues. The next step is to extract focused metric and trace snapshots for MG01@1614858000 and MG02@1614857820 (and quick log/error counts around ±60s) to determine if any resource KPI strongly breached its threshold and to identify the earliest fault point.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For the two spike timestamps do three focused queries using kernel tables (metric_window, metric_thresholds, trace_window, log_window, error_logs_window):\n1) Metrics: For timestamp=1614858000 and cmdb_id='MG01', and for timestamp=1614857820 and cmdb_id='MG02', join metric_window rows at those timestamps with metric_thresholds to get global_p95; compute exceed = (value >= global_p95) and exceed_ratio = (value - global_p95) / max(global_p95,1e-9). Return only rows where exceed is True, include columns: timestamp, datetime_utc8, cmdb_id, kpi_name, value, global_p95, exceed_ratio. Sort by timestamp asc then exceed_ratio desc. Limit to top 50 rows.\n2) Traces: For cmdb_id='MG01' at timestamp=1614858000 and cmdb_id='MG02' at timestamp=1614857820, return all trace_window rows with columns: timestamp, datetime_utc8, cmdb_id, trace_name, value. Sort by timestamp asc then value desc. Limit to top 50 rows.\n3) Logs/Error counts: For each spike timestamp, count rows in log_window and error_logs_window within ±60 seconds for cmdb_id in ['MG01','MG02']. Return compact counts: spike_timestamp, cmdb_id, log_count, error_log_count. If any logs/error_logs exist, return up to 5 example rows for that component and time window (columns: timestamp, datetime_utc8, cmdb_id, log_name, value) or (timestamp, datetime_utc8, cmdb_id, message). Keep outputs compact and limit rows as specified." }

